Log in to the Server:


  1. Throughout the live contest, we are going to use the server (neural.pstat.ucsb.edu) to update your prediction on the ERP of the S&P500 and trading strategy about how much to buy or sell. First of all, check your inbox and search for “ERP Contest - Username and Password to Connect to the Server” like this:



  1. Download the attached file Connecting to server via SSH.pdf and follow instructions. You might need an application for the SSH (Secure Shell) protocol such as Terminal on Mac and PuTTY on Windows. Your login information are also attached to the email. Open the Google Doc 2020_teams_login and check for your Username and Password.

  2. Start your application. Here, I use PuTTY on Windows. Write down the server name neural.pstat.ucsb.edu.



  1. Log in using your Username and Password. If you are successfully logged in then you will see like this:




Upload your Files to the Server:


  1. During the live contest, you have to update your prediction and trading strategy every (trading) day. To do this, you need the following 5-6 files:
    • Your code: R, python, etc. It takes ucsbdata.csv and returns output.txt. ex) demo_server.R
    • A shell executable file: a file that excutes your code. ex) runner.sh (in this file it consists of one command line Rscript demo_server.R)
    • A data file ucsbdata.csv.
    • Your data file if you develop new variables (optional). ex) your_data.csv
    • checker.py: a program that will check your output.
    • checker.sh: a file that will excute checker.py.

  2. Go to our webpage and download checker.zip. You will find checker.py and checker.sh in it.



  1. Select the Data tab on our webpace and download the data file ucsbdata.csv. For my convenience, I rename it as ucsbdata_demo.csv.



  1. Create shell executable file. For example, to run my R code demo_server.R, I open an editor program like NotePad and write down Rscript demo_server.R and save it as a .sh format.



  1. Prepare your own data file if needed (optional).

  2. Put these files together in one directory.



  1. Run cmd and go to the directory where the files are stored. My address is C:\ERP so I use cd C:\ERP.



  1. Copy these file to the server by executing the following two commands: path C:\Program Files\PuTTY and pscp -r * ylee@neural.pstat.ucsb.edu:/home/ylee. You should replace C:\Program Files\PuTTY by the address where PuTTY is installed on your computer and ylee by your Username. Don’t forget to insert your Password.



  1. Going back to PuTTY, check that all the files are uploaded in your home directory by using ls.




Run your Code on the Server:


  1. Now, you are ready to run your program. Execute your .sh file by typing sh runner.sh. Make sure that an output file output.txt is created.



  1. Before running a checker program, you may print output.txt and see what’s inside by using cat output.txt. Three numbers should be (1) a predicted ERP of the S&P500, (2) the amount of the S&P500 index fund to buy, and (3) the amount to sell in order.



  1. Finally, excute checker.sh to confirm that your output file output.txt is correct by using sh checker.sh.
